turns: Hillary Clinton's security detail arrived at a fruit processing company in suburban Des Moines, Iowa on Tuesday with a second Scooby van, a mechanically identical vehicle to the one commonly used for her protection. The second Scooby van has a nearly identical Secret Service escort vehicle, and both vehicles have raised roofs, deep-tinted windows, and New York license plates. The first Scooby van, known as Scooby-one, is a GMC, while the second, Scooby-two, is a Chevrolet. Both vans are used to confuse potential attackers, with the Secret Service deploying duplicates of aircraft and cars it uses to transport VIPs, including Marine One, the president's customized helicopter, which usually travels with two decoys. Clinton's campaign stressed that the use of the second Scooby van does not affect taxpayers' expenses, as her constant protection is due to her former position as a former first family member, not her service in the Senate or State Department. The Clinton convoy includes both Scooby vans and four black Suburbans, as well as a white minivan, with Scooby-Two's driver bringing up the rear to allow another car to pull in front of him, and the GMC van's blue and red flashing lights coming on when the car in front of him stopped at a red light. The extra Scooby van and other security measures are intended to protect Clinton during her campaign and add to the confusion for potential attackers.

A family of six in Georgia lost their home in a fire early on Monday morning. The mother, who was enrolled in school to complete her degree in business management, is now struggling to find a stable place to live for her and her children as they have been turned away by shelters. The mother has started a GoFundMe page to request assistance and has so far raised $4,619.

Australian couple abandoned a boy born through surrogacy in India and were repeatedly told that the child would be left stateless. Consular staff in India were aware that the couple was from New South Wales, where it is illegal to enter into international surrogacy arrangements. The couple sought citizenship for a baby girl but told consular staff they would be leaving her twin brother behind because they could not afford him. The boy was left behind in India and was eventually recovered by his biological parents. The story is similar to the recent case of Gammy, who was born to a surrogate mother in Thailand and whose Australian parents only brought back his twin sister.The

Kecil, a one-year-old baby orangutan, was rejected by his natural mother and two surrogate mothers. However, he found love and a new mother in Maggie, a 53-year-old orangutan who had already raised four children and another surrogate. The two have formed an inseparable bond, and Maggie has proved to be a great parent to Kecil. They will be going on display to the public for the first time this weekend.

Paris Saint-Germain star Javier Pastore has dismissed Eric Cantona's suggestion that he is the greatest footballer on the planet, insisting Lionel Messi and Cristiano Ronaldo are a class above him. His comments come ahead of his side's European clash against Barcelona in the Nou Camp.

A midwife has won a decade-long battle to change guidelines on when to clamp the umbilical cord during childbirth. Amanda Burleigh believed that clamping the cord within seconds of delivery was harmful andiskaὶd without evidence. She worked with other medics to gather evidence that immediate cord-clamping could be harmful, especially for premature babies. NICE has now changed its guidelines to state that doctors and midwives should not routinely clamp the cord 'earlier than one minute from the birth of the baby'. The cord should be clamped within five minutes, but left longer if the mother requests. The change means that mothers get the chance to hold their babies for a moment while still connected to them.

French President Francois Hollande has vowed to show no mercy if French peacekeepers are found guilty of sexual assaulting starving children in the Central African Republic. Fourteen soldiers have been accused of abusing children as young as nine as they begged for something to eat, according to a French judicial source. The French defence ministry denied covering up the scandal and launched an investigation into the case. UN employee Anders Kompass, who turned over a leaked report on the abuse to French authorities, was subsequently suspended. It's unclear what the reaction from the Central African Republic government was, but a government member said that if the allegations are true, it would be 'horrible and unacceptable' and French soldiers cannot 'behave like this in a country where they came to help civilians.'

A shocking video has surfaced of a Texas pastor's wife attempting to resurrect a two-year-old boy who had died. The woman, identified as Aracely Meza, was arrested and charged with injury to a child by omission for the incident which occurred at a home operating as a church. The boy's mother had previously dropped him off at the home, where services were presided over by pastors Daniel and Aracely Meza. The investigation is ongoing and more information is expected to be released on Tuesday.

Professional snooker players John Higgins and Graeme Dott both won their first-round matches at the Betfred World Championship in Sheffield on Sunday, leading the Scottish charge. Four-time champion Higgins, who has not won a major tournament in over three years, defeated Robert Milkins 10-5. Higgins looked strong and confident and broke his opponent's slightly patchy form to progress to the second round. Higgins stated that he enjoyed a better night's sleep in the run-up to the tournament than he has recently, but said that he is 'daring to dream' of another world title. On the other hand, unseeded Dott struggled initially and had to come from 6-3 down to edge out Ricky Walden 10-8. Higgins acknowledged that Dott's victory was 'massive' for Scottish snooker in light of Dott's double-world-title status and the support he receives from the stadium when playing at home.

Barcelona footballers Neymar, Dani Alves and Adriano were all smiles after their 1-0 win over Celta Vigo, but their choice of matching denim outfits was met with mix reactions. The Brazilian trio all started the game and played a key role in the victory which saw Barcelona go top of La Liga. However, player Jeremy Mathieu admitted that the team played poorly and blamed the international break, while praising his defensive partner Gerard Pique. Dani Alves also posted a picture of himself with Neymar and Adriano on Instagram, with the caption "a great day at work".

It is reported that Chelsea manager Jose Mourinho is planning to make a summer move for Atletico Madrid midfielder Koke. The club's technical director Michael Emenalo has been watching Koke play during Atletico's victory against Deportivo, according to Spanish newspaper AS. Mourinho is reportedly planning to offer second-choice left-back Filipe Luis as part of the deal, but it is unclear if Atletico would be interested in the offer. Koke has a release clause of around £50 million and Chelsea could be willing to pay this as Mourinho looks to add to a midfield that has looked tired at times this season. Mourinho is a long-time admirer of Koke, who has been an important player for Atletico in recent years.

Tom Ballard plans to climb the second highest mountain in the world, K2, 20 years after his mother's death while attempting the same feat. Alison Hargreaves was swept to her death in 1995 while descending from the peak of K2. Tom Ballard, one of the world's most accomplished climbers, is now training for the summit. His mother, Alison Hargreaves, was a revered figure in the climbing world and was only the second person to climb Mount Everest without sherpas or bottled oxygen. While she was pregnant with her son, she climbed the north face of the Eiger in the Swiss Alps. Mr Ballard was just six years old when his mother died. He now plans to follow in her footsteps and become the second person to climb K2 after his mother. Mr Ballard's decision to take on dangerous climbs while raising a young family was criticized by some, but his mother shrugged off the flak.

It is claimed that there is up to 100 billion barrels of oil beneath the Weald Basin area of England, a region known as "Britain's Dallas". This could potentially meet up to a third of Britain's oil demand within 15 years. The discovery was made by UKOG, who have a 30% stake in the site. They believe that the oilfield holds 158 million barrels per square mile, equating to 100 billion barrels across the basin. The site is situated near Gatwick Airport and test drilling is currently underway. The British Geological Survey has estimated the basin holds just 4.4 billion barrels of shale oil, while a study by Imperial College London suggests a maximum of 40 billion barrels. The exploration is expected to create many thousands of jobs and could potentially reduce reliance on oil from the Middle East and Russia. However, industry experts remain skeptical of the claims and one described them as "overly optimistic." Profits from the oil will go to the Government, who owns the land under the homes of residents. The government will receive taxes on the oil extracted and may grant oil companies licenses to excavate oil and keep profits. Oil companies do not have to pay surface landowners unless they want to base their drilling site on the land. Fracking is a more intrusive method of extracting oil, and if it is used, the companies must agree to provide "community benefits" which includes building a playground or school, and is seen as compensation for residents. Oil companies need to consult communities if they plan to undertake fracking in the area and gain planning permission from the local council.

The British Veterinary Association (BVA) has withdrawn its support for the shooting of free-running badgers in controversial pilot culls in Somerset and Gloucestershire. The BVA concluded that the first two years of culling had not demonstrated that ‘controlled shooting’ of free-running badgers could be effective and humane. The BVA still supports badger culling to tackle tuberculosis in cattle. The Environment Secretary, Liz Truss, promised to roll out more culls across the country if the Tories win the election, but the BVA's ongoing support for cage-trapping and shooting is "regrettable". Ms Truss pledged any future Conservative government would "take the difficult decisions to deal with this disease" and said the Government's strategy included cattle movement controls, vaccination in 'edge' areas around disease hotspots, and culling where the disease is rife.

It is suggested that modern technology and social media are often distractions that can negatively affect budding relationships rather than assisting them. The article provides a list of ways to avoid showing oneself up on dates, including keeping phones off the table and avoiding online checking of relationships.

Tottenham Hotspur will be without several key players, including Kyle Walker and Hugo Lloris, for their home clash against Aston Villa in the Premier League on Saturday. Meanwhile, Tim Sherwood's Aston Villa side will be without a number of players, including Alan Hutton, Ashley Westwood, Scott Sinclair, Carles Gil, and Libor Kozak, as they return to White Hart Lane for the first time since being sacked last summer. Odds for the match favour Tottenham, with Aston Villa at 5/1, and the game is expected to be a tight contest with both sides having a relatively strong defensive record. Tottenham have won their last five matches against Aston Villa and have the highest-scoring player in the league in Harry Kane, who has 16 goals in 15 appearances this season. However, Aston Villa have had a poor season so far and have conceded three goals in each of their last two matches, which could give Tottenham some opportunities to score.

A mother who made the heartbreaking decision to give birth to her sick baby at 20 weeks had her wedding dress redesigned so her tiny daughter could be buried in it. Annabelle Cox was born prematurely weighing just 290 grams and passed away soon after. Her parents decided to deliver her early to end her suffering, and contacted Angel Gowns, a not-for-profit organization that turns donated wedding gowns into outfits for babies who die too soon. Angel Gowns created a replica dress for the family to have in their house and Ms. Cox looks at it every day to remember her daughter. The family also took photos with Annabelle in her gown before the funeral. Angel Gowns is currently donating outfits to more than 80 hospitals and funeral homes across Australia. To donate your wedding dress or volunteer with Angel Gowns, visit [www.angelgownprogram.com.au](http://www.angelgownprogram.com.au).

A black police constable in Wiltshire, UK has won a race discrimination case against the Wiltshire Police force after he was not promoted due to the color of his skin. The tribunal ruled that the officer was unlawfully discriminated against and that he was passed over for promotion in favor of white colleagues after his internal assessments were downgraded to make him appear unworthy. The officer had previously raised concerns about the discrimination but was not taken seriously. The Chief Constable of Wiltshire Police has said that the force will learn lessons from the case and is committed to increasing diversity in the force to better reflect the communities they serve.

A parent taught their newborn daughter how to suck a plastic water bottle instead of teaching her the alphabet. The video has been watched over 190,000 times and received positive comments from viewers.

A set of unique photos taken nearly 100 years before much of Bristol's historic centre was destroyed by bombing have surfaced. The photos, captured between 1850 and 1855 by photographer Hugh Owen, show the waterfront, city centre, and St Mary Redcliffe church, as well as other buildings in the area. Many of the buildings have changed dramatically between the 19th century and today, but certain areas, such as High Street and Sleep Street, remain virtually unchanged. The albumen prints were made in the 1870s from the original paper negatives of the early 1850s, and some of the photos show the same buildings that are still standing today, such as the Fourteen Stars Tavern, which was pulled down in 1857. The albumen prints are due to go up for auction tomorrow in Cirencester.

It appears that a Businessman named Harvey Boulter, who has a vendetta against Liam Fox, is now targeting another Tory candidate, Tom Tugendhat, by donating £30,000 to the UKIP candidate challenging Fox in his Somerset seat and spending another £30,000 to support the UKIP candidate against Tugendhat in Tonbridge and West Malling, Kent. Boulter is reportedly seeking revenge against Fox for a libel case in which Fox won a substantial award from Boulter. The story states that Boulter is trying to defeat "a golden boy" Tory candidate, but does not provide more specific information on the reason why he views Tugendhat as such. A Tory Party spokesman declined to comment on the story.

Aston Villa manager Tim Sherwood has replied to a letter from a six-year-old fan who applied for the job after Paul Lambert was sacked. Charlie Pye, from Leamington Spa, would have accepted the role in exchange for a chocolate bar, a signed football, a WWE wrestling figure and some sweets. Although Charlie was not successful in securing the job, Sherwood congratulated the young fan for his "knowledge of the game" and wrote that he would be an "ideal candidate" for the role. Sherwood also mentioned Charlie's appointment as Norton Lindsey captain and wished him success in his football career. The 6-year-old would have appointed his parents as assistant managers if given the job.

Atletico Madrid beat basement side Cordoba 2-0 and leapfrogged Valencia to move into third place in the La Liga standings, with Antoine Griezmann scoring both goals. Valencia have a game in hand and can reclaim third spot with a win over Villarreal on Sunday. Cordoba remain stuck in last place with 10 consecutive defeats. Atletico also kept up the pressure on second-placed Real Madrid and league leaders Barcelona, who each have 64 points, with Real hosting Granada and Barcelona playing Celta Vigo on Sunday. Sevilla, the only side unbeaten at home in La Liga this season, beat Athletic Bilbao 2-0 and have 58 points in fifth.

An 18-year-old mother with a three-year-old son died from multiple organ failure after taking the illegal Class B drug Mephedrone (M-Cat or Meow Meow) at a house party in Tamworth. One girl has been arrested on suspicion of supplying drugs, but the victim's cousin claims her drink was spiked. The police are awaiting the result of the post-mortem examination, and the family is devastated by the loss of their loved one. The use of M-Cat has previously been warned about in Tamworth, with a raid two months ago resulting in the discovery of 4lbs of the drug.

A Tokyo playground has been found to have dangerously high levels of radiation, with readings of up to 480 microsieverts per hour, nearly half the recommended annual limit of exposure for a person. The cause of the radiation is unknown, but authorities suspect it could be coming from something buried underneath the park. The city has set up a health advice office and has taken the playground behind orange barricades. Radiation concerns have persisted in Japan since the 2011 Fukushima disaster.

Amir Khan has accused Kell Brook of calling him out for the "one big payday" and not truly recognizing his credentials as a boxer. He also believes that Brook needs him for the bigger payday and that he is not yet a big name in the UK. Khan has denied that he will fight Chris Algieri in May and has other options in mind. He also expressed that he does not have a specific deadline for a fight with Brook and that he is not avoiding him. Khan also believes that Brook is not yet a big name in the UK and has failed to make a mark in the US.

A Dallas architect named Matt Mooney has created a stunningly modern 3,700-square-foot three-bedroom home out of 14 shipping containers. The house, dubbed "PV14", also features a 1,400 sq ft roof deck, a 40ft long swimming pool on the ground floor, and 360 degree views of White Rock Lake and the downtown skyline. The house's walls and ceilings were left exposed, and columns were placed around the house to restore structural integrity to the materials. Spray foam was used for insulation between the building layers. The house was designed to show what the materials used to build it look like, and the upstairs levels were outfitted with maple wood floors to complement the views of the nearby park and lake.

The shipping container house, 'PV14', also features a 1,400 sq ft roof deck that can fit up to 150 people and a 40ft long swimming pool on the ground floor. The house also has a 360 degree view of White Rock Lake and the sparkling lights of the city's downtown.

It is reported that Liverpool's Jordon Ibe is close to signing a new five-year contract with the club. Ibe has impressed since returning to Liverpool this season and will sign the new deal by the end of the week. Liverpool also expect to announce Jordan Henderson's new contract and are close to finalising an extension for Martin Skrtel.

Rik Mayall, a British comedian known for his role in "The New Statesman," died last year without leaving a valid will, putting his family at risk of paying inheritance tax. His estate is now subject to government rules for intestacy, and his wife and children would inherit the available assets. According to these rules, his wife would receive £250,000, and his children would inherit half the remaining value of the estate, potentially triggering an inheritance tax bill. However, Mayall's family could avoid this tax by splitting the estate through a legal agreement. Mayall's personal life experienced a few challenges, including a quad-bike accident in 1998 and a near-fatal head injury. Despite this, he unexpectedly made a full recovery and returned to work.

A group of evacuees, mostly Indian nationals, scrambled onto an Air India plane at the Sanaa airport, carrying only their carry-on luggage. The passengers were evacuated due to the ongoing fighting in Yemen, where Saudi Arabia is bombing the country in an attempt to drive out Houthi rebels. Air India was particularly active in evacuations because many Indian nationals work in other countries. Over the last few days, India has evacuated around 2,500 people from Yemen, and flights are going to Djibouti, a small African nation. The evacuees are leaving behind much more than just luggage, as the fighting and lack of electricity have made life in the capital city of Sanaa unbearable. The Saudi air force gave Air India a four-hour window to travel to and from Sanaa, and the landing strips and airport terminal were untouched by Saudi bombs, but buildings on the outskirts of the airport and planes along the airstrip had been blown to bits. Despite the chaos, evacuees were greeted by Air India crew members in pressed uniforms and flight attendants in makeup, offering drinks as if they were on a vacation flight.

An Italian priest has been dismissed from a religious order in Taranto after an online lover contacted the church authorities with a dossier containing alleged evidence of sex with prostitutes and explicit gay web chats. The priest, who was gay, was accused of organizing orgies with priests and a Swiss Guard, although church authorities have not said anyone else was involved. The laborer claimed that the priest had tried to seduce him and even convinced him to leave his girlfriend.

A new study published in JAMA found no link between the MMR vaccine and autism, even among high-risk children who have older siblings with autism. The study included 95,000 children and found no increased risk of autism after MMR vaccination. The findings are consistent with previous studies that have ruled out a link between the MMR vaccine and autism. Despite the consistent evidence, concerns over vaccine safety continue, and many parents believe the MMR vaccine is a contributing cause of autism. The study also found that children with older siblings with autism are less likely to get vaccinated, and the MMR vaccination rate for children with affected siblings was lower than for those without affected siblings.

A 12-year-old girl was tied up, beaten and raped by seven ISIS fighters after being kidnapped from her home in the Iraq region of Yazidi. The study undertaken by Human Rights Watch found that ISIS is kidnapping women and children as young as eight, forcing them to marry and convert to Islam and raping them repeatedly – sometimes picking their victims’ names out of a hand in a sick lottery. Yazidi women and girls have been separated from their families, forced to convert to Islam and repeatedly raped by ISIS fighters, which amounts to war crimes. Some of the children interviewed said they were ‘owned’ and raped by seven different men and tried to kill themselves while in captivity to avoid rape. Despite recent attempts to release those who managed to escape, they are still having to cope with the trauma they faced, and there is a lack of provision for psycho-social treatment.

On Monday morning, a shooting incident took place at Wayne Community College in Goldsboro, North Carolina. One person was killed, and a former student who did not graduate from the college, Kenneth Stancil, is a suspect in the shooting. Stancil entered the building carrying a long-barreled gun and fired one shot, which killed long-time employee Ron Lane. According to police, Stancil is white, approximately 5'11" with a goatee, and has a tattoo over his left eye. The suspect is still at large, and an active shooter situation exists. SWAT teams rushed to the college, and students were evacuated building by building. Goldsboro Sheriff's Department, military style SWAT vehicles and police from around Wayne County descended on the community college. The lockdown was lifted as of about 10.30am ET. The authorities have urged the public not to approach the suspect.

The new chief executive of Rotherham council may be paid up to £40,000 more than the outgoing boss due to recent negative publicity from the grooming scandal. The council will now offer up to £200,000 to candidates, rather than the £160,000 enjoyed by the former chief boss. The rest of the cabinet resigned in February, after a government report said the council was 'not fit for purpose' and 'in denial' about exploitation, mainly of white girls by men of Pakistani origin. The new chief executive might be offered this additional compensation due to recent negative publicity.

Chelsea's midfielder Cesc Fabregas will wear a special protective face mask after breaking his nose, the mask was created by an orthopedic center in Milan called Ortholabsport and its craftsmen Stefano Duchini and Lucilla Pezzoni, the mask has Fabregas's initial and squad number 'C4' and it became famous for its work with former Chelsea players Torres and Ba, as well as Manchester City, Fulham and European clubs including Inter Milan and Shakhtar Donetsk. Fabregas suffered the break during Chelsea's win over Stoke City, but played on for the entire 90 minutes. He traveled to Milan with Chelsea's medical director Paco Biosca to have the mask fitted. John Terry had to wear a protective face mask after fracturing a cheekbone in 2007, and Fernando Torres also worn a mask during his time at Chelsea. Diego Costa is expected to miss at least two weeks of action with hamstring trouble.

Andros Townsend scored a wonder strike for England against Italy in a friendly match, silencing his critics, including Paul Merson, and demonstrating his ability to pay back Roy Hodgson's faith in him. Despite a topsy-turvy season, Townsend remains a key player for Tottenham and the England national team, and his goal in Turin showed that he is capable of reaching the heights he first achieved on the international stage.

A husband who is accused of trying to murder his cheating wife wrote her a letter from prison, requesting that she send him a suit for his trial. The letter, which was posted from prison on February 4th this year, asked his wife to gather some of his belongings and give them to his son, including a "decent jumper" and his "beige casual jacket." He also asked for his "blue suit" and "three ties that will go with the suit," which he said he needed for the trial. The letter went on to say that he hopes his wife's recovery continues and that she will always remain in his heart. The case is being heard in Brighton Crown Court.

The UK is set to open its first three proton beam therapy centers, after five-year-old Ashya King made a miraculous recovery from brain cancer after receiving treatment in Prague. Proton Partners International, a UK-based company, will operate the centers in Cardiff, London, and Northumberland by 2017, with the first center in Cardiff operational by next year. The announcement comes just weeks after Ashya's parents, who wanted him to have proton beam therapy instead of conventional treatment, fled with him to Spain and then traveled to the Czech Republic for the treatment. The UK currently sends patients abroad for proton beam therapy at a cost of around £100,000 per patient. The government has announced plans to create two NHS proton beam therapy units, which will open in 2018.

It is reported that London Ambulance Service has been recruiting paramedics in Australia and has hired around 300 paramedics so far. This is because of a shortage of paramedics in the UK and the increasing demand for emergency care. Managers from the service have filled 225 vacant posts with applicants from Sydney and Melbourne. The selection process was held at five-star hotels and applicants were informed via email within 8 hours whether they had a job. This recruitment drive is not a long-term solution, but it is helping to fill the skills shortage while more people are trained to become paramedics in the UK.The

Chelsea Football Club has turned to the latest fitness technology to carry them over the line in their pursuit of the Premier League title. The Blues, who currently lead the chasing pack by seven points with a game in hand over their closest rivals, have announced a partnership with leading wellness solutions provider Technogym, who have kitted out their Cobham training ground with state-of-the-art equipment. Players including Eden Hazard and Nemanja Matic have been pictured being put through their paces, while new signing Juan Cuadrado and defender Kurt Zouma have been using the new equipment. Chelsea fitness coach Carlos Lalin has hailed the club's partnership with Technogym, while Technogym's founder and President Nerio Alessandri said they share a strong dedication to performance. Blues defender Nemanja Matic has been using weights and resistance training to get himself in shape for Sunday's visit of Manchester United, while Diego Costa and Eden Hazard have been nominated for the PFA Player of the Year awards. Hazard is the clear favourite for the award, thanks to his consistently brilliant form throughout the season.

The study by psychologists at the University of Missouri has found that infants as young as 13 months old can understand complex social situations such as bullying, friendship, and being a bystander. The study using puppets indicated that the newborns had strong feelings about how people should deal with a character who hits others. The study also found that babies learn from the unexpected and use prior knowledge to form predictions, learning better when they are surprised. Previous studies have shown that much younger babies and newborn animals have surprising amounts of knowledge about maths and physics, including whether an object should be able to pass through a solid wall. The King's College London study found that children who can accurately depict the human form at the age of four are more likely to be brighter in their teenage years, with a definite correlation between the drawing scores and the intelligence scores.

Manny Pacquiao decided to train on the streets of Los Angeles by running along the trail at Griffith Park ahead of his highly-anticipated fight against Floyd Mayweather. Pacquiao swapped the gym for the great outdoors as he worked on his fitness and stamina in preparation for what could be a lengthy bout against his welterweight rival. Pacquiao was joined by several fitness fanatics during his run around the North America's largest urban park, shadow boxing in front of interested spectators to show off his skills. Pacquiao was also tested on his core strength and worked on his aerobic endurance.

Biso, a cat who became stuck in a wall at the Mohamed Naguib metro station in Cairo in 2010, has finally been freed after five years. The cat survived thanks to an elderly man named Uncle Abdo who fed him scraps of food every day. The cat's plight came to the attention of animal activists after a picture of his tail hanging from behind the wall was posted on Facebook last month. Animal rights activist Mounira Shehata and fellow activists Marwa Elgebaly and Rania el-Kordy went to the station to save the cat, but Biso quickly ran away after being rescued.

At least 35 workers were killed at a dairy factory in Yemen when Saudi Arabian warplanes continued to bomb Shiite rebel positions in both the north and south of the country. Today's airstrikes targeted rebel-controlled army camps in the Red Sea port city of Hodeida and hit warehouses belonging to a factory that produces dairy products. The jets drew return fire from anti-aircraft guns as the Saudi-led campaign to defeat the Iran-backed Shiite rebels loyal to Yemen's deposed president Ali Abdullah Saleh entered its seventh day. The attack on the dairy factory comes as Saudi Arabia hinted that it was prepared to launch a ground invasion in Yemen in the hope of forcing the Houthi rebels to allow current president, Abed Rabbo Mansour Hadi to return to the country, after he fled the southern port city of Aden last week. The Hodeida death toll included at least 35 workers who were killed in the explosion.

A truck crash on an elevated highway in Boston caused delays for hundreds of morning commuters. The collision occurred on Interstate 93 southbound in the city's Dorchester neighborhood and both drivers were taken to the hospital with non-life-threatening injuries. Replacement shuttle buses were run for southbound passengers, causing long queues to form. The incident is being investigated by state troopers and no charges have been filed.The
Saracens director of rugby Mark McCall praised his young players after their European

The decomposing bodies of four alleged terrorists who killed 148 people at a Kenyan university were paraded in front of a crowded primary school today. The authorities drove the naked, bloated corpses of the men around the town in a pickup truck from the mortuary to Garissa Primary School. This follows the rescue of a survivor, Cynthia Cheroitich, who hid in a wardrobe for two days drinking body lotion to survive. The attackers were suspected to be members of al-Shabaab, a militant Islamist group that claimed responsibility for the attack, stating that it was in retaliation for Kenyan troops fighting them in Somalia. Seven people were arrested, including five Kenyans and two Somalis. The interior ministry stated that all three were associates of Islamist teacher Mohamed Mohamud, who is believed to have masterminded the attack. President Uhuru Kenyatta called on Kenyan Muslims to help prevent radicalization, saying, "Radicalization that breeds terrorism is not conducted in the bush at night. It occurs in

It is important for Arsenal to make a decision on Petr Cech this summer if they want to sign him. The Chelsea goalkeeper will meet with Jose Mourinho at the end of the season to confirm his plans to leave, and other clubs such as Liverpool, Paris Saint-Germain, Roma, and Inter Milan are also interested in Cech. However, the keeper's valuation will likely be high, and Chelsea may be hesitant to sell to a Premier League rival. While Cech has indicated that he will consider moving to the Emirates Stadium, it remains to be seen if Chelsea will agree to sell him to Arsenal.

Frankie Dettori will focus on the British flat season this summer, while Sheikh Joaan Al Thani has signed up Gregory Benoist to ride the horses which race under his Al Shaqab banner in France. Thierry Jarnet will continue to ride Treve, with the exception of Ectot, which was unplaced for Al Shaqab in the Arc last year. AP McCoy had his final race at Cheltenham, finishing seventh, and is retiring from racing.

Lois Lilienstein, one of the stars of the Canadian preschool TV show "Sharon, Lois & Bram's Elephant Show," has died at the age of 78 due to a rare form of cancer. Her son, David Lilienstein, stated that his mother died peacefully and not in pain. Lilienstein and her husband moved to Toronto in 1996, where she continued to perform with her singing trio. Sally Catto, general manager of programming at CBC Television, paid tribute to Lilienstein for her significant contribution to Canadian kids' TV. The show "Sharon, Lois & Bram's Elephant Show" ran on CBC in Canada from 1984 to 1989, and continued in reruns on Nickelodeon stateside until 1995.

French freediver Guillaume Néry jumped into the Dean's Blue Hole in the Bahamas, the second deepest underwater sinkhole in the world. He didn't use scuba gear and held his breath for an unknown amount of time while swimming back to the surface. He practiced intensive breathing exercises to increase lung capacity and followed a high fruit and vegetable diet. However, he revealed later that he didn't reach the bottom of the hole in the video. Freediving is a form of underwater diving where no scuba gear or breathing apparatus is used.

A suicide bomber killed at least 33 people and injured over 100 others in Jalalabad, Afghanistan on April 8th, 2017. The attack targeted government workers at the Kabul Bank. ISIS claimed responsibility for the attack, with the group's offshoot Wilayat Khorasan taking credit. Taliban spokesman distanced his group from the attack. UN condemned the violence and referred to the continuing use of suicide attacks in densely populated areas as a possible war crime. Laura Wells, the plus-size model and environmental scientist, has launched a new swimwear collection called Coral Reef. The collection is made entirely from 100% recycled materials, inspired by the ocean and ranges in sizes from 10 to 24. The collaboration with Swimsuits For All's trend range, SwimSexy, features plunging V-necklines and high-waisted bottoms. The collection caters to all shapes, and the primary challenge was finding environmentally-friendly material while keeping prices affordable.

The TrackYourDose app is a new app that records a user's personal radiation exposure from medical examinations, changes in location, and flights. The app calculates a user's ambient dose equivalent, which is measured in microsieverts (µSv), and tracks all the relevant types of radiation, in particular neutron radiation produced in the atmosphere. The app gives an estimate of the radiation exposure a user will receive during a flight, including information on the solar activity for the flight. This app was developed by the company esooka. It uses a mathematical model developed by scientists and meteorologists from the Physikalisch-Technische Bundesanstalt (PTB) in Germany and the University Oulu, Finland, to calculate radiation levels. The app is available for iOS and costs £1.49 ($1.99).

Blue Bell Ice Cream has suspended operations at an Oklahoma production facility that has been connected to a foodborne illness that caused the deaths of three people. The company had previously recalled ten products from a plant in Brenham, Texas due to the illness, which was traced back to a 3-ounce cup of ice cream contaminated with listeriosis. The CDC has identified six patients with listeriosis between 2010 and 2014 that was indistinguishable from that found in the 3-ounce cup ice cream product traced to the Oklahoma plant. The investigation is ongoing to determine whether these illnesses are related to exposure to Blue Bell products. The company will conduct a thorough examination of its Oklahoma plant and will notify the FDA once the investigation is complete. The recalled ice cream had been shipped to institutional accounts such as hospitals in 23 states that comprise less than 5 per cent of the company's sales.

Jon Hamm, the star of the TV drama Mad Men, was involved in a hazing incident at a University of Texas at Austin fraternity in 1990, according to court documents uncovered by Star magazine. The documents claim that Hamm, who was then 20 and a sophomore at the university, participated in a brutal physical assault on a prospective pledge as part of a hazing ritual. Hamm and seven other fraternity members were accused of paddling, humiliating and beating the pledge, with Hamm allegedly leading him around the room by a hammer hooked under his genitals. Three members of the fraternity were sentenced to 30 days in prison. Hamm reached a plea deal with authorities in 1995 and the charges were dismissed. In recent years, the stresses of playing the role of Don Draper on Mad Men have taken a toll on Hamm's psyche.

The UK has summoned the Argentine ambassador to London to complain about recent comments made by the Argentine president regarding the Falkland Islands. The president has threatened to take legal action against British and US oil companies operating in the waters surrounding the islands. The UK Foreign Secretary has stated that the islanders have a right to develop their oil and gas industry, and that the UK will protect them from Argentine bullying. The Argentine president's comments came on the 33rd anniversary of the start of the Falklands War.

Delta Flight 2522 landed at LaGuardia Airport with an odor of smoke, causing some anxiety among passengers and crew. Emergency workers surrounded the plane and used a thermal imaging camera to locate a potential heat source. As the situation unfolded, the Delta crew provided updates, and passengers remained calm. The firefighters put on protective suits and inspected the plane for about 45 minutes before deplaning passengers normally. The plane was taken out of service for inspection and maintenance.

David Luiz, the Brazilian defender for Paris Saint-Germain, is recovering from a torn hamstring injury. He posted a picture of himself on Instagram with a man bun hairstyle, which his teammate Lucas Moura joked about by allowing his followers to give him a nickname for the hairstyle. The injury will keep Luiz out of action for at least four weeks and may cause him to miss up to eight league matches, which could impact Paris Saint-Germain's title defense.

US President Barack Obama stated that diplomacy was the best option to address Iran's contested nuclear program. He emphasized the importance of long-term negotiations and a deal that is based on unprecedented verification. Obama acknowledged that there would be a debate in the US but committed to keeping Congress informed. Israel's Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has criticized the agreement and expressed concern that it would threaten the survival of the state of Israel. Critics, including Saudi Arabia and some US lawmakers, have suggested Iran may cheat and that the deal may increase the risk of nuclear proliferation in the region. However, Obama views the deal as a historic understanding that will require many details to be worked out before it is signed on June 30.

A 12-year-old girl with Leukemia has been kicked out of a private Catholic school in Michigan for low attendance and poor academic performance despite her illness. The school claims they made many accommodations for her but they were not enough to help her. Her parents say the school failed their child and filed a complaint with the Office of Civil Rights. The girl's mother says she is still recovering from her treatments and not missing school to have fun, but because she feels ill.

Passive smoking doesn't only harm humans, but also affects plants. Plants near cigarette smoke sources have been shown to take up nicotine from the soil and smoke. This can lead to high levels of nicotine in food crops and plant-derived products, despite nicotine being banned as an insecticide. The researchers used peppermint plants and found that nicotine concentrations in the plants were several times higher than the maximum residue level set by European authorities after fumigation with cigarette smoke. The results suggest that high levels of nicotine in plants may be due to other sources apart from illegal insecticide use, such as horizontal transfer of natural products.

The more aggressive of the two chameleons, seen on the right, wins the fight, but the defeated chameleon escapes and is shown crawling across a concrete wall and clambering onto a tree branch.

Scotland youth international Jack Cosgrove has agreed to join Edinburgh rugby club on a two-year deal from Worcester Warriors, the 20-year-old prop has played nine times for Scotland Under 20s. Cosgrove wants to add strength to the Edinburgh squad and learn from the club's experienced players, he also mentioned the positive buzz at the club and the European final reach by the team.

He is being separated from other prisoners and his tattoos are being examined for gang affiliations. It appears that Manchester City's manager, Manuel Pellegrini, has stated that the club's young Academy players are not yet ready to step into the first-team squad. As a result, Jason Denayer, who has impressed while playing for Celtic on loan this season from Manchester City, may soon find himself returning from his loan deal to fill the gap. Celtic are keen to retain the services of the 19-year-old Belgian defender, but face an uphill struggle due to City's focus on investing in homegrown talent. Denayer falls into this category despite hailing from Belgium, making him all the more attractive to City next season. Despite Pellegrini's comments, he acknowledged that young players are important to the club and that they will likely have important players coming from the Academy in the future.

Ander Herrera, the Manchester United midfielder, reveals that he wears his full name, Ander Herrera, on the back of his shirt for superstitious reasons following his successful spell at Athletic Bilbao. He began using this name three years ago and notes that it coincided with a good period at Bilbao. Herrera has recently burst into United's starting eleven, contributing to the team's successful streak with seven goals so far this season.

Despite being defeated 6-1 in the first leg and losing 7-4 on aggregate to Bayern Munich in the Champions League quarter-final, Porto's fans gave the team a hero's welcome upon their return to Portugal. The team was greeted with cheers and chants of pride from the fans, who were proud of their club's run in the tournament, despite the loss. Porto's coach Julen Lopetegui admitsthat the team was beaten by a much better team but he was proud of what the team showed in the Champions League.

The BBC has been criticized for creating a computer game simulating the dangerous journey of Syrian refugees trying to leave their war-torn country and reach Europe. The game portrays grim outcomes such as women being sold to militia and refugees being beaten and thrown into the Mediterranean. Experts believe the game turns the suffering of millions into a "children's game" and slammed the BBC for creating it. The game was made in-house and has received over a million hits a week. The Syrian conflict has resulted in the deaths of up to 300,000 people since it began over four years ago, and millions of people have been displaced.

Boston Marathon bomber Dzhokar Tsarnaev has been given another opportunity to avoid the death penalty by two of his victims, Jessica Kensky and Patrick Downes. The couple, who both lost legs in the 2013 attack, have joined the family of an eight-year-old boy who was killed in the blast in calling for life in prison without parole instead of the death penalty. They say that the continued pursuit of the death penalty would bring years of appeals and prolong reliving the painful experience for themselves and other victims. The statement is similar to that of the family of Martin Richard, who died in the attack, and comes just days after the two-year anniversary of the bombing. The defense team for Tsarnaev is led by Judy Clarke, who has previously helped high-profile clients avoid the death penalty. Experts say that the jury may be swayed towards life in prison due to Massachusetts' generally liberal view on the death penalty.

Hamdi Ulukaya, the founder and CEO of Chobani, has settled a lawsuit filed by his ex-wife, Ayse Giray, who claimed a 53% stake in the company. The settlement came just before a court ruling on whether Giray could be named a shareholder in Chobani's predecessor company, Euphrates. The lawsuit was filed in 2012 and claimed that Giray had loaned $500,000 to Ulukaya that helped him start his food business. Chobani has been facing business problems, including a product recall in 2013 that led to negative EBITDA of $87 million in the fourth quarter. The settlement is a private matter and the details of the settlement have not been disclosed.

Diego Costa has been diagnosed with a hamstring injury and is expected to miss Chelsea's game against Arsenal, which could be a key game in the title race. He is likely to be fit to return within two weeks. As a result, Chelsea may give him an extended break to prevent future injuries. The club is considering other options, such as using the striker sparingly through the season's end, after a similar injury caused him to miss time earlier this season.

The England C team, also known as the National Game XI, England Semi-Pro and England Non-League, is under threat of being axed due to the FA's spending review. The team costs £30,000 a year and the FA has identified it as a potential area for savings to fund Greg Dyke's masterplan to improve grassroots football through the use of 3G pitches in urban coaching hubs. The team is managed by Paul Fairclough and selects players outside of the Football League aged 23 and under. The team only plays three or four times a year and some friendly fixtures have raised concerns regarding the elaborate travel involved. The team has had some notable players, including George Boyd, Craig Mackail-Smith, and Steve Morison, who all played for their respective countries after playing for the England C team. However, Boyd and Mackail-Smith also played for Scotland and Wales, respectively, and Morison played for Wales. Former Leicester winger Steve Guppy also won one senior England cap after playing once for his country at non-league level.

James Haskell, the London Wasps captain, posted a photo on his Instagram page dressed as Robert Downey Jr.'s character Iron Man in anticipation of the new Avengers: Age of Ultron movie. The movie premiered at Westfield London shopping center with a cast including Robert Downey Jr., Chris Hemsworth, and Scarlett Johansson. Haskell returned to Wasps for the 2012 season after spells with Stade Francais, Ricoh Black Rams, and Highlanders in New Zealand. He first joined Wasps in 2002 and spent eight seasons with the club before moving to Stade Francais, Ricoh Black Rams, and Highlanders. Haskell has 57 caps for the England rugby team.

A woman recorded a video of another woman launching into a tirade against Muslims on a Sydney train, with the woman defending the Muslim couple and instructing the woman to be quiet. The Muslim couple told the woman they were 'very grateful' for her stand. The incident was subsequently reported to the police and Sydney Trains.

A civil lawsuit is moving forward against former New England Patriots player Aaron Hernandez, who was convicted of first-degree murder in the 2013 killing of Odin Lloyd. Hernandez's mother is expected to be called to testify in the case. The mother of Odin Lloyd, Ursula Ward, filed the civil lawsuit to look into the murder of her son and wants to hear Hernandez's testimony in person. Hernandez did not testify at his criminal trial, despite having a $40 million contract, and the mother of his fiancée is also a witness in the case. The team was originally named in the suit, but it was dismissed after they agreed to release any money owed to Hernandez to the Lloyd family. The lawsuit seeks unspecified damages. Britain has discovered oil in the Falklands, a discovery that is likely to escalate tensions with Argentina over the ownership of the islands. Argentina claims that firms operating off the Falklands coast are acting 'illegally' in Argentine territory and has warned of a "very live threat" from Britain. The find, announced by British firms that share the exploration area, could be worth billions of pounds and will increase fears of renewed conflict over the British overseas territory. The discovery comes exactly 33 years after Argentina invaded the islands and just days after Defence Secretary Michael Fallon warned of a "very live threat" from Argentina. The discovery of oil will likely increase the rhetoric and sabre-rattling from Argentina, and Britain has pledged to defend the Falklands with an upgrade of a surface-to-air missile system and the deployment of two Chinook helicopters. Oil expert Charlie Sharp said that oil is always found in difficult places, geographically and politically, but that has never worried the oil industry.

A three-legged cat named Freeman was mauled to death by two dogs in a brutal attack in Tarring, West Sussex. The horrific attack was captured on CCTV and shows the woman who owns the dogs collecting them from the neighbor's lawn, leaving the cat to die in agony. The woman who owns the dogs has been identified, and the police are investigating the incident. Freeman was a beloved family pet, and his owner, Tracy Lynch, is devastated by his death. She is shocked that the dog owners did not check on the cat after the attack. The police have revealed that the large dogs, which were running loose, were possibly Dobermans, and the woman who collected them turned up in a blue car. The attack is being investigated as an act of cruelty.

A Chinese woman is an internet sensation after she shared her life with her pet pig that she dresses, walks and even sleeps with every day. The woman, who calls herself Zhu Diandian online, has raised her beloved Five Flowers since it was a piglet and the porker has now grown to 187lbs (13st). Her husband is understood to be 'tolerant' of the relationship. However, the same can't be said of her pet dog, who often peers enviously at the pig through a baby gate. Her photos of her and the pig in bed have 13,000 'retweets' and almost 9,000 comments, mostly supportive of her unusual pet. She works at a publishing company in Beijing and has almost 40,000 followers on Weibo.
